They have hot dogs!

40:00.441 --> 40:03.194
- What's "cola"?
- Poison water.

40:03.277 --> 40:04.612
Can I have the grilled cheese?

40:04.737 --> 40:05.696
No.

40:05.780 --> 40:07.281
What's a "milkshake"?

40:07.364 --> 40:09.366
Dad, can I have a hamburger and fries?

40:09.450 --> 40:10.451
Can I have pancakes?

40:11.952 --> 40:14.205
Okay, everyone up. We're outta here.

40:14.288 --> 40:15.706
What? No, why?

40:15.790 --> 40:19.293
Because there's no actual food
on this menu. Let's go.

41:22.815 --> 41:24.108
Are you okay?

41:26.026 --> 41:28.529
An old man's having a heart attack!
Call 911!

41:29.196 --> 41:30.531
Call 911!

41:31.448 --> 41:33.200
Everyone, get back!

41:34.118 --> 41:35.119
My pills!

42:00.352 --> 42:02.313
- I'm okay.
- He's okay now.

42:02.479 --> 42:04.398
- Sir?
- Sorry.

42:05.733 --> 42:07.193
Sir?

42:07.735 --> 42:08.986
Sir?

42:09.528 --> 42:11.697
- Sir?
- Sorry about the fuss.

42:12.072 --> 42:13.741
Are you sure we can't get you
an ambulance or anything?

42:13.866 --> 42:16.160
No, I just forgot to take my pills.

42:16.243 --> 42:18.245
I'm fine now, really.

42:38.265 --> 42:40.184
Where else can we improve?

42:40.267 --> 42:43.270
Flawed exit strategy.
Everyone went out the same doors.

42:43.395 --> 42:45.439
No one utilized
the loading dock area at all.

42:45.564 --> 42:47.691
- If it got blocked, we'd all be trapped.
- Mmm-hmm.

42:47.775 --> 42:49.693
Inadequately planned extraction point.

42:49.777 --> 42:51.695
We probably shouldn't have
all gone directly to the bus.

42:51.779 --> 42:54.198
Predetermined pick-ups
would have been much less risky.

42:54.281 --> 42:56.742
On the plus side, Mission:
Free the Food, accomplished.

42:56.867 --> 42:59.286
- Mission: Free the Food!
- Top marks all around.

42:59.370 --> 43:02.122
Now, if you'd all do me a favor
and close your eyes.

43:06.794 --> 43:08.796
You may open your eyes.

43:09.755 --> 43:11.507
Happy Noam Chomsky Day.

43:11.590 --> 43:13.467
But Noam was born on December 7th.

43:13.592 --> 43:14.969
Well, we're celebrating it today.

43:17.221 --> 43:18.222
Yes!

43:28.107 --> 43:29.566
So good.

43:41.287 --> 43:45.124
Uncle Noam, it's the day of your birth!

43:45.207 --> 43:48.377
Uncle Noam, it's the day of your birth!

43:48.460 --> 43:52.631
Uncle Noam, it's the day
of your birth! Uncle Noam!

43:52.715 --> 43:57.720
Uncle Noam, Uncle Noam!

43:57.845 --> 43:59.013
All hail!

44:01.432 --> 44:03.600
- Here we go. Nai.
- Yes.

44:03.684 --> 44:05.060
- Bodevan.
- Thank you.

44:05.144 --> 44:06.145
Rellian.

44:08.480 --> 44:09.648
Rell.

44:09.732 --> 44:12.401
Kielyr, Vespyr, Zaj.

44:12.484 --> 44:13.485
All right, go for it.

44:14.737 --> 44:15.988
Dad!

44:16.447 --> 44:19.450
Fifty-five-pound pull,
laminated wood and glass.

44:19.616 --> 44:20.617
Whoa!

44:21.327 --> 44:22.995
A KA-BAR fighting knife?

44:23.078 --> 44:24.747
- That's right.
- Thanks, Dad!

44:24.830 --> 44:26.290
It's so beautiful.

44:26.623 --> 44:30.586
Seven-inch blade, partially serrated,
well-balanced if you dip when you cut.

44:31.754 --> 44:32.755
Pictures.

44:35.007 --> 44:36.008
Oh.

44:36.091 --> 44:38.844
Those are Black Storm broadheads.
Razor sharp.

44:41.930 --> 44:44.975
What kind of crazy person celebrates
Noam Chomsky's birthday

44:45.059 --> 44:46.977
like it's some kind of official holiday?

44:47.519 --> 44:50.147
Why can't we celebrate Christmas
like the rest of the entire world?

44:50.522 --> 44:54.318
You would prefer to celebrate
a magical fictitious elf

44:54.401 --> 44:56.570
instead of a living humanitarian

44:56.653 --> 44:59.656
who's done so much to promote
human rights and understanding?

45:00.491 --> 45:02.451
Okay, well, let's have a discourse.

45:05.788 --> 45:07.873
- Forget it.
- No, explain.

45:09.083 --> 45:11.210
Take the opportunity to make your case.

45:11.293 --> 45:12.920
We're all open to hearing your arguments.

45:13.003 --> 45:14.922
And if they're valid and you persuade us,

45:15.005 --> 45:18.133
I'm sure we'd all be willing
to change our minds. Right?

45:18.801 --> 45:21.345
- Yeah.
- Use your words.

45:49.540 --> 45:50.624
Ah!

45:54.128 --> 45:57.589
- Yes! Thanks, Dad!
- You're welcome.

46:25.868 --> 46:26.952
Do you guys need a hand?

46:27.035 --> 46:29.079
- No, we're fine.
- No, we got it.

46:30.789 --> 46:31.790
All right.

46:31.874 --> 46:34.334
- Jackson, not at the table.
- Hey.

46:34.835 --> 46:37.171
- Jackson.
- All right.

46:38.422 --> 46:40.591
Well, I am so happy

46:40.674 --> 46:44.052
that our family is together.

46:44.803 --> 46:46.430
Thanks for putting on this feast.

46:47.306 --> 46:51.101
It's all local and, um,
organic and non-GMO, so...

46:51.185 --> 46:52.686
How did you kill those chickens?

46:52.936 --> 46:54.688
With an ax or a knife?

46:57.900 --> 47:01.737
I didn't have to kill the chickens.

47:03.906 --> 47:06.450
It's a rotisserie chicken, so you buy it.

47:06.533 --> 47:09.453
It's already dead. Or cooked. On a thing.

47:13.999 --> 47:16.001
- Dig in.
- All right.

47:18.378 --> 47:20.714
- Ben, some wine?
- Please.

47:24.801 --> 47:26.887
Dad, can I have some wine?

47:26.970 --> 47:30.140
- Sure, why not?
- Ben. No.

47:30.224 --> 47:31.517
Children don't drink wine.

47:31.600 --> 47:35.437
In France, and other countries, children
drink small amounts of wine all the time.

47:35.521 --> 47:37.814
It's a digestive. It's not crack.

47:37.898 --> 47:39.233
What's crack?

47:39.900 --> 47:44.112
Crack is a crystallized,
highly addictive derivative

47:44.196 --> 47:45.489
of the stimulant cocaine.

47:45.781 --> 47:49.785
In the mid-1980s, it accelerated
the decimation of inner-city neighborhoods.

47:49.868 --> 47:52.621
Crackheads, some of them kids
just like you guys,

47:52.704 --> 47:56.375
were killing each other over
nothing, over their Nikes.

47:56.667 --> 47:58.544
They killed each other for Nike?

47:58.627 --> 48:00.546
The Greek winged goddess of victory?

48:03.382 --> 48:05.759
- Stop.
- He's joking, right?

48:07.803 --> 48:10.597
- They're like Adidas.
- Who's Adidas?

48:10.847 --> 48:12.474
You're serious?

48:14.560 --> 48:15.769
They're shoes.

48:22.025 --> 48:23.026
Now.

48:24.528 --> 48:25.696
Ben.

48:25.779 --> 48:27.239
We're, uh...

48:28.699 --> 48:31.493
I'm sorry for your loss.

48:31.577 --> 48:33.370
We're devastated.

48:34.997 --> 48:39.293
- We're just so sorry.
- Thank you, Dave.

48:42.170 --> 48:44.715
I don't know what else to say. I'm like...

48:45.799 --> 48:49.136
It's okay. We all know
you had issues with Leslie.

48:49.678 --> 48:51.597
- What?
- It's not a secret.

48:51.680 --> 48:54.057
I wouldn't say that. Why would you...

48:54.141 --> 48:55.934
Last time we saw you,
you called her a "fucking bitch."

48:56.018 --> 48:58.687
- Ben.
- What? It's fine.

48:59.396 --> 49:01.315
My kids remember. Don't you, guys?

49:01.648 --> 49:02.774
Yeah.

49:02.858 --> 49:06.653
Wait, no. I said that...

49:08.155 --> 49:12.659
We were all having a huge,
uh, fight about sugar.

49:12.909 --> 49:16.538
I had given the kids some,
what, Frosted Mini-Wheats.

49:16.663 --> 49:18.832
And the extremity of her position...

49:20.334 --> 49:22.711
She was yelling at me,
she pushed me, and I said...

49:22.836 --> 49:23.879
"Don't be such a fucking bitch."

49:24.004 --> 49:25.005
- Ben.
- I didn't say that.

49:25.088 --> 49:27.966
They're just words.
Your words, but just words.

49:28.050 --> 49:29.134
Not spoken in this house.

49:29.217 --> 49:32.387
No, it's inappropriate for him
to say that in front of the kids.

49:34.890 --> 49:38.018
Absolutely, understood.
It won't happen again.

49:38.101 --> 49:39.102
Okay.

49:49.404 --> 49:51.239
Dad, how did Aunt Leslie die?

49:51.365 --> 49:53.200
Well, Aunt Leslie was sick

49:53.283 --> 49:57.663
and she had, uh,
complications from her sickness.

49:57.746 --> 49:58.789
Yeah.

50:01.541 --> 50:03.043
She had a mental illness.

50:03.460 --> 50:05.212
Bipolar affective disorder.

50:05.462 --> 50:07.464
We think it started
right after Bo was born.

50:07.547 --> 50:10.217
Probably a form of postpartum psychosis.

50:11.093 --> 50:14.388
She'd have violent mood
swings ranging from mania,

50:14.471 --> 50:18.892
where she'd be elated and make
elaborate plans for the future,

50:18.975 --> 50:21.770
to severe depression where
she'd become almost catatonic.

50:23.230 --> 50:25.107
Utterly without hope.

50:26.733 --> 50:29.194
We didn't understand what was happening.

50:29.277 --> 50:31.738
We don't need to talk about
this in front of the children.

50:31.822 --> 50:33.323
These are details that are...

50:33.407 --> 50:37.661
The doctors, uh, put her in the hospital,

50:37.744 --> 50:41.707
they gave her medicine,
but she was really sick.

50:41.790 --> 50:46.461
- Yeah.
- And she died.

50:49.798 --> 50:51.258
Sick people die.

50:55.137 --> 50:58.306
Sometimes they... They die.

50:59.182 --> 51:01.435
She died 'cause of...

51:03.520 --> 51:05.814
Because of... Because of the sickness.

51:05.939 --> 51:06.940
She slit her wrists.

51:07.441 --> 51:09.651
She killed herself. That's what happened.

51:10.277 --> 51:11.278
Or that.

51:25.625 --> 51:26.960
Excuse me.

51:40.348 --> 51:42.476
- Here you go, sweetie.
- Thank you.

51:45.187 --> 51:46.271
Bo.

51:56.281 --> 51:58.492
- To Mom.
- To Mom.

52:03.163 --> 52:04.331
Shh.

52:09.503 --> 52:11.004
Combo!

52:14.299 --> 52:15.759
Extreme combo!

52:17.177 --> 52:18.804
Victory!

52:21.473 --> 52:23.099
We're just doing the best we can, Ben!

52:23.225 --> 52:24.518
- That's all anybody is doing!
- So am I!

52:24.643 --> 52:26.061
Just the best that we know how.

52:26.186 --> 52:28.313
I'm really sorry it doesn't live up
to your high standards!

52:28.396 --> 52:30.148
I tell the truth to my kids.
I don't lie to my kids.

52:30.232 --> 52:32.901
Protecting children from certain concepts

52:33.026 --> 52:35.654
that they are too young to understand
is not lying to them.

52:35.737 --> 52:38.198
Guys! We have neighbors, okay?

52:38.865 --> 52:42.118
Look, it's a very hard time right now.

52:42.202 --> 52:43.495
Everybody's still a little raw.

52:43.578 --> 52:47.707
Can we just try to, come on,
put this to bed, all right?

52:54.339 --> 52:55.549
I apologize.

52:57.050 --> 53:00.387
I'm sorry for not respecting the way
you guys do things in your home.

53:03.431 --> 53:05.225
Thank you for saying that.

53:11.189 --> 53:14.985
I know Leslie had been sick for a long time,
but I cannot imagine how difficult

53:15.068 --> 53:16.570
this time must be for you.

53:32.294 --> 53:34.212
Guys, what are you doing?

53:34.296 --> 53:35.922
We're sleeping under the stars.

53:36.923 --> 53:37.883
But...

53:37.966 --> 53:39.759
We made up the rec room downstairs,

53:39.885 --> 53:41.261
- for a sleepover.
- Yeah.

53:42.429 --> 53:45.807
We're fine here. We're fine.

53:48.059 --> 53:49.144
Good.

54:03.617 --> 54:05.327
Why do they have to take showers?

54:05.452 --> 54:07.412
They're not taking a shower.
I mean, it looks like a shower,

54:07.537 --> 54:09.289
but it's really a gas chamber.

54:09.372 --> 54:10.665
Jackson, put that thing away

54:10.749 --> 54:13.293
or I'm going to put it in the microwave,
press "Popcorn."

54:13.376 --> 54:14.461
All right.

54:14.586 --> 54:16.129
Actually, why don't you take your cousins

54:16.212 --> 54:18.381
and go show them your action figure guys?

54:18.465 --> 54:19.549
Why?

54:19.633 --> 54:20.884
Because they may never
have seen them before.

54:20.967 --> 54:21.968
It might be fun.

54:22.052 --> 54:24.095
So, can we play Xbox afterwards?

54:24.471 --> 54:25.722
One game. Go.

54:25.805 --> 54:26.890
Yes!

54:28.642 --> 54:31.478
- Thank you.
- Yeah, try it.

54:39.986 --> 54:42.322
- How are the kids doing?
- They're strong.

54:44.115 --> 54:46.576
How long have you been out there,
wherever it is you're living now?

54:46.660 --> 54:48.662
We left Boulder when Bo was three.

54:49.663 --> 54:53.416
And then we were on that farm
we had in Oregon until he was eight.

54:53.500 --> 54:55.502
So, we bought the land
in the forest 10 years ago.

54:55.627 --> 54:57.128
How do you still have money?

54:58.838 --> 55:00.090
We only buy what we need.

55:00.173 --> 55:03.009
Look, Harper and I have been talking.

55:04.636 --> 55:06.429
The kids need structure, stability.

55:06.513 --> 55:08.515
They need to go to a real school,

55:08.640 --> 55:10.433
- so they can get real jobs.
- Oh, for Christ's sake.

55:10.517 --> 55:11.810
You're going to get them killed!

55:11.977 --> 55:13.186
Whoa.

55:20.110 --> 55:21.528
I'm sorry.

55:21.653 --> 55:23.697
But your kids are without a mother now.

55:23.822 --> 55:26.700
I don't think you have any idea
what you're doing to them.

55:26.825 --> 55:29.369
I'm saving their lives,
that's what I'm doing.

55:29.452 --> 55:31.788
Ben, you sound so ridiculous.

55:31.871 --> 55:35.625
Is knowing how to set a broken bone
or how to treat a severe burn ridiculous?

55:35.709 --> 55:39.337
Knowing how to navigate by the stars
in total darkness, that's ridiculous?

55:39.838 --> 55:43.216
How to identify edible plants,
how to make clothes from animal skins,

55:43.299 --> 55:45.385
how to survive in the forest
with nothing but a knife?

55:45.510 --> 55:46.720
That's ridiculous to you?

55:47.137 --> 55:48.138
Jesus.

55:48.221 --> 55:51.808
They have the cardiovascular and muscular
endurance levels of elite athletes.

55:51.891 --> 55:53.977
Who cares? They're children.

55:54.060 --> 55:56.938
They need to go to school,
they need to learn about the world.

55:59.733 --> 56:02.193
Justin? Jackson?

56:02.527 --> 56:04.904
Would you please
come down here for a second?

56:15.165 --> 56:16.249
What?

56:17.083 --> 56:18.835
How old are you now, Jackson?

56:18.918 --> 56:20.086
Thirteen.

56:22.172 --> 56:24.424
Can you tell me what
the Bill of Rights is?

56:27.761 --> 56:30.096
What something costs? I guess.

56:30.221 --> 56:31.598
That's a good guess.

56:31.723 --> 56:34.017
- Justin, you're in high school?
- Yeah.

56:34.100 --> 56:37.312
- Do you like your school?
- It's whatever.

56:39.272 --> 56:40.732
Do you know what the Bill of Rights is?

56:42.525 --> 56:44.611
It's a government thing, right?

56:44.736 --> 56:47.363
Like, rights that people
have in America and stuff...

56:47.947 --> 56:51.034
- Yep. Hey, Zaja!
- Yes!

56:51.451 --> 56:54.120
Would you please come down here
a moment, sweetie?

56:56.623 --> 56:58.416
I wanted to ask you a quick question.

56:59.209 --> 57:01.419
Zaja just turned eight, by the way.

57:02.879 --> 57:04.047
Bill of Rights.

57:04.923 --> 57:07.383
Amendment 1, Congress shall make no law

57:07.467 --> 57:12.097
respecting an establishment of religion
or prohibiting the free exercise thereof,

57:12.555 --> 57:13.807
or abridging the freedom of...

57:13.890 --> 57:17.477
Stop. Regurgitating memorized
amendments isn't what I'm asking for.

57:17.811 --> 57:20.480
Just tell me something
about it in your own words.

57:22.816 --> 57:26.152
Without the Bill of Rights,
we'd be more like China.

57:26.319 --> 57:29.364
Here, at least,
we don't have warrantless searches,

57:29.447 --> 57:33.493
we have free speech, citizens are protected
from cruel and unusual punishments...

57:33.618 --> 57:35.078
- That's enough.
- Are protected...

57:35.161 --> 57:36.996
Wait a minute. Zaja...

57:37.080 --> 57:38.164
How would you characterize

57:38.248 --> 57:41.417
the 2010 Supreme Court
decision on Citizens United?

57:42.794 --> 57:44.754
Corporations have
the same rights as people,

57:44.838 --> 57:46.840
so there's no spending limit
on candidates.

57:47.340 --> 57:50.426
Which means our country
is ruled by corporations

57:50.510 --> 57:52.679
and their lobbyists who fund candidates

57:52.762 --> 57:54.430
and command their fealty
by demanding that...

57:54.514 --> 57:55.890
Jesus Christ.

57:56.141 --> 57:57.517
You made your point, we get it.

57:59.644 --> 58:02.021
It's very impressive. All of you.

59:51.798 --> 59:52.799
Is that yoga?

59:56.386 --> 59:58.888
Your breath, they call it pranayama.

59:58.972 --> 01:00:01.766
It flows with your movements, your asana.

01:00:01.933 --> 01:00:04.227
It's supposed to connect the mind
and the body to fuel your Samadhi.

01:00:06.437 --> 01:00:07.772
Does that really work?

01:00:28.167 --> 01:00:29.335
I'm Claire.

01:00:31.629 --> 01:00:34.299
- Bodevan.
- "Bodevan"?

01:00:35.174 --> 01:00:36.843
What kind of a name is that?

01:00:41.472 --> 01:00:42.974
My parents made it up.

01:00:44.183 --> 01:00:45.852
That's weird. Why?

01:00:46.185 --> 01:00:47.395
Our names are unique.

01:00:48.187 --> 01:00:50.315
There's only one of us in the whole world.

01:00:52.358 --> 01:00:53.651
That's really weird.

01:01:07.832 --> 01:01:09.876
What kind of music do you listen to?

01:01:11.461 --> 01:01:12.837
Mostly Bach.

01:01:13.629 --> 01:01:17.050
Mainly the Goldberg Variations,
especially Glenn Gould's versions.

01:01:17.550 --> 01:01:21.471
I also like the Unaccompanied Cello Suites,
preferably when played by Yo-Yo Ma.

01:01:26.351 --> 01:01:27.810
Where are you from?

01:01:30.563 --> 01:01:33.066
Most recently in Paris, in the Marais.

01:01:34.275 --> 01:01:35.526
Near Victor Hugo's house.

01:01:37.070 --> 01:01:40.073
We're just back in the States
because of my dad's sabbatical.

01:01:40.198 --> 01:01:44.243
He's writing a book on Dr. Spock.

01:01:44.327 --> 01:01:46.746
Oh. I love Star Trek, it's awesome.

01:01:48.623 --> 01:01:49.624
Which star?

01:01:50.208 --> 01:01:51.751
You know, Spock.

01:01:52.251 --> 01:01:54.670
The guy with the ears,
he's from Star Trek.

01:01:54.754 --> 01:01:56.589
No, Dr. Spock was from Connecticut.

01:01:56.672 --> 01:01:59.926
Right after Yale, he wrote
Baby and Child Care in 1947.

01:02:00.009 --> 01:02:02.220
It's one of the seminal books
on child-rearing.

01:02:02.428 --> 01:02:06.182
I was talking about that old TV show.

01:02:07.600 --> 01:02:08.893
Oh.

01:02:09.102 --> 01:02:10.853
- "Child-rearing."
- Of course.

01:02:10.937 --> 01:02:13.106
Yeah, I know that one, it's...

01:02:14.315 --> 01:02:15.316
Awesome.

01:02:20.405 --> 01:02:21.489
And what about your mom?

01:02:26.619 --> 01:02:28.287
I can't talk about it.

01:02:30.456 --> 01:02:32.375
She works for the U.S. government.

01:02:33.835 --> 01:02:36.963
I can't talk about it due
to its highly classified nature.

01:02:37.046 --> 01:02:38.089
Seriously?

01:02:38.548 --> 01:02:40.174
I can't say any more.

01:02:40.258 --> 01:02:42.468
I don't even know that much myself.

01:02:43.010 --> 01:02:44.095
It's, um...

01:02:44.929 --> 01:02:47.348
I shouldn't have told you.

01:02:48.766 --> 01:02:50.643
You can't tell anyone.

01:03:22.049 --> 01:03:23.217
Are you okay?

01:03:26.846 --> 01:03:28.514
Yeah.

01:03:51.245 --> 01:03:52.330
Okay.

01:03:53.206 --> 01:03:54.707
Follow me. We have to be quiet.

01:04:03.382 --> 01:04:05.051
It's almost midnight.

01:04:07.887 --> 01:04:10.181
I sincerely hope you two lovebirds

01:04:10.264 --> 01:04:12.558
haven't been doing
what I think you've been doing.

01:04:18.940 --> 01:04:20.233
I know what you think.

01:04:20.316 --> 01:04:22.652
But I know that your daughter
has taught me many things just now.

01:04:23.069 --> 01:04:26.197
She has broadened my mind,
she has helped me grow.

01:04:26.280 --> 01:04:28.241
When we just kissed
for the first time just then,

01:04:28.324 --> 01:04:30.409
